---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "../../components/Header.astro";
import Insights from "../../components/Insights.astro";
import Contact from "../../components/Contact.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import click_depth_chart from "../../assets/form-questions.png";
import AuthorBlock from "../../components/AuthorBlock.astro";
import "../../styles/global.css";
import "../../styles/charts.css";

import DistributionChart from "../../components/DistributionChart.astro";
import {
    formData,
    buckets,
    sizeLabels,
    selectivityLabels,
} from "../../data/form-analysis-data.js";

// --- Page-Specific SEO & Content Data ---
const title =
    "2025 Inquiry Form Benchmarks: An In-Depth Look at 750+ Slate Schools";
const description =
    "A deep dive into common inquiry form practices, from average length and common questions to UX choices and consent language. See how your RFI form compares to national benchmarks.";
const pubDate = "2025-10-01";
const image = click_depth_chart;
const alt =
    "An illustration representing data analysis of college inquiry forms.";
const absoluteImageUrl = new URL(image.src, Astro.site).href;
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} image={absoluteImageUrl}>
    <script
        type="application/ld+json"
        slot="head-scripts"
        set:html={JSON.stringify({
            "@context": "https://schema.org",
            "@type": "BlogPosting",
            headline: title,
            description: description,
            image: absoluteImageUrl,
            author: {
                "@type": "Person",
                name: "Tristan Deveney",
                url: new URL("/about#deveney-bio", Astro.site).href,
            },
            publisher: {
                "@type": "Organization",
                name: "Predicate Higher Ed",
                logo: {
                    "@type": "ImageObject",
                    url: new URL("/assets/logo.svg", Astro.site).href,
                },
            },
            datePublished: new Date(pubDate).toISOString(),
            dateModified: new Date(pubDate).toISOString(),
        })}
    />

    <Header />
    <main>
        <section class="content-section article-page">
            <div class="narrow-container">
                <div class="article-header">
                    <Image
                        src={image}
                        alt={alt}
                        class="article-feature-image"
                    />
                </div>
                <div class="article-content">
                    <h1>{title}</h1>
                    <p class="article-meta">Published on October 1, 2025</p>
                    <p>
                        After a prospective student has <a
                            href="/articles/click-depth/"
                            >clicked through to your inquiry form</a
                        >, what can they expect to find? How many questions will
                        they have to answer in order to join your mailing list?
                        What kinds of information will they be prompted to
                        provide?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        As part of our analysis of more than 750 Slate inquiry
                        forms in 2025, we looked at how different institution
                        types approached the length and structure of their
                        inquiry forms, including, in the case of certain fields, <em
                            >how</em
                        > the fields are mapped.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To help understand variations across institution types,
                        we've broken down institutions based on Carnegie
                        Classification of Institutions of Higher Education® and
                        by IPEDS data on selectivity and institution size.
                    </p>

                    <p class="attribution">
                        Source: Carnegie Classification of Institutions of
                        Higher Education®, American Council on Education.
                        <a href="https://carnegieclassifications.acenet.edu"
                            >carnegieclassifications.acenet.edu</a
                        >
                    </p>

                    <div class="toc-container">
                        <p class="toc-title">In This Article</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <a href="#form-length-core"
                                    >Form Length & Core Questions</a
                                >
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <a href="#form-length">1. Form Length</a
                                        >
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <a href="#academic-timing"
                                            >2. Academic & Timing Information</a
                                        >
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <a href="#audience-communication"
                                    >Audience & Communication</a
                                >
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <a href="#user-identification"
                                            >3. Identifying the User</a
                                        >
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <a href="#parent-info"
                                            >4. Parent Information</a
                                        >
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <a href="#sms-consent"
                                            >5. SMS & Texting Consent</a
                                        >
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <a href="#marketing-ux"
                                    >Marketing & User Experience</a
                                >
                                <ul>
                                    <li>
                                        <a href="#marketing-attribution"
                                            >6. Marketing Attribution</a
                                        >
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <a href="#optional-step"
                                            >7. The Optional Step</a
                                        >
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li><a href="#conclusion">Conclusion</a></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <h2 id="form-length-core">Form Length & Core Questions</h2>

                    <h3 id="form-length">1. Form Length</h3>
                    <p>
                        Across all Slate institutions that had a single-page
                        form, the average inquiry form contained <strong
                            >16.3 questions</strong
                        >. This count includes questions that appeared based on
                        conditional logic for prospective first-year students
                        who were opting in to provide core contact information
                        for themselves and a parent. If a form appeared to offer
                        additional sections for students wishing to provide more
                        detailed information about athletics, extracurriculars,
                        or specialized pre-professional interests, those were
                        excluded from the count.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        When forms are grouped into five buckets based on
                        length, we found that Baccalaureate Colleges (Arts &
                        Sciences Focus) were more likely than other types to
                        have forms at the two extremes, with either fewer than
                        10 questions or more than 25 questions:
                    </p>
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="Form Length Distribution by Carnegie Classification"
                        caption="For institutions in each Carnegie Classification, bars indicate the percentage of inquiry forms that fall into different length buckets."
                        data={formData.formLength.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.formLength)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.formLength}
                        legendLabel="# of Qs"
                    />
                    <p>
                        When grouping by size and selectivity, it becomes
                        clearer that the most selective institutions
                        (particularly the smallest) are the likeliest to have
                        longer forms:
                    </p>
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="Form Length Distribution by Size and Selectivity"
                        caption="Smaller, more selective institutions tend toward longer forms, while larger, less selective institutions show a wider range of form lengths."
                        data={formData.formLength.sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.formLength)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.formLength}
                        legendLabel="# of Qs"
                    />

                    <h3 id="academic-timing">
                        2. Academic & Timing Information
                    </h3>
                    <p>
                        Asking for a prospective student's academic and timing
                        interests are overwhelmingly common practices. <strong
                            >98%</strong
                        >
                        of forms ask for an intended <strong>entry term</strong
                        >, and
                        <strong>87%</strong> ask for a <strong
                            >program of interest</strong
                        >.
                    </p>

                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="Forms That Ask for Program of Interest"
                        caption="The strong majority of institutions, regardless of type, collect academic interest on their inquiry forms, though R1s and baccalaureate colleges (arts & sciences focus) did not in roughly a quarter of cases."
                        data={formData.academicInterest.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="Forms That Ask for Program of Interest by Size & Selectivity"
                        caption="Collection of academic interest is widespread across all segments, although one exception was highly selective medium-sized institution, where only 50% collected major."
                        data={formData.academicInterest
                            .sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />

                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="Forms That Ask for Entry Term"
                        caption="Nearly all institutions collect the student's intended start term on their inquiry forms."
                        data={formData.entryTerm.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="Forms That Ask for Entry Term by Size & Selectivity"
                        caption="Asking for an intended entry term is a standard practice across the board."
                        data={formData.entryTerm.sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />

                    <h2 id="audience-communication">
                        Audience & Communication
                    </h2>

                    <h3 id="user-identification">
                        3. Identifying the User: Parent or Student?
                    </h3>
                    <p>
                        One challenge with inquiry forms is that the person
                        filling out the form might not be the student: parents,
                        counselors, or alumni might sign up or refer a student;
                        if the wording of questions isn't clear, this can
                        sometimes lead to inquiry records being created in the
                        name of those individuals, rather than in the name of
                        the student.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Some schools attempt to solve for this challenge by
                        asking an identifying question, usually at the top of
                        the form, and then either conditionally displaying
                        different sets of questions or routing the parent or
                        other individual to a dedicated form. We wanted to
                        measure how common this practice had become as of 2025,
                        and whether it was more common at certain types of
                        institutions than others.
                    </p>
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="Forms That Ask 'Parent or Student?' by Carnegie Classification"
                        caption="Percentage of forms that include a field to identify the user type."
                        data={formData.parentIdentifier.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="Forms That Ask 'Parent or Student?' by Size & Selectivity"
                        caption="While not common, there was a greater tendency at larger institutions to ask identifying questions, while the smaller, more selective institutions were the least likely to do so."
                        data={formData.parentIdentifier
                            .sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />

                    <h3 id="parent-info">4. Parent & Family Information</h3>
                    <p>
                        As schools seek to engage parents directly, collecting
                        parent information at the point of inquiry can help
                        create opportunities for engagement earlier in the
                        recruitment process.
                    </p><p>
                        For many institutions that implemented Slate pre-COVID,
                        it was common to create custom person-scoped fields to
                        store parent contact information, with the standard
                        relation table only being mapped at point of
                        application. This approach was often recommended in
                        order to help avoid data issues (inconsistent email
                        addresses or spellings of parent names) from lower
                        quality sources like inquiry forms, compared to the
                        application. Discrepancies can result in duplicate
                        relation records if relationship type is not collected,
                        for example, or if first name and last name are
                        inconsistent (see <a
                            href="https://knowledge.technolutions.net/docs/relationship-records#mapping-to-relationship-fields-in-form-events"
                            >this KB article</a
                        >)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        While many schools do still use these custom fields, the
                        majority of those that collect parent information on the
                        inquiry form do so by mapping directly to the relation
                        table. With parent information stored using relation
                        records, it becomes possible to build recipient list
                        queries using the relation base for parent
                        communications, following the Technolutions best
                        practice for <a
                            href="https://knowledge.technolutions.net/v1/docs/en/messaging-relationship-records"
                            >Messaging Relationship Records</a
                        >.
                    </p>
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="Parent Information Collection Method by Carnegie Classification"
                        caption="How institutions collect and store parent/family information from inquiry forms."
                        data={formData.parentInfo.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.parentInfo)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.parentInfo}
                        legendLabel="Method"
                    />
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="Parent Information Collection Method by Size & Selectivity"
                        caption="With many of the smaller, more selective institutions implementing Slate 10+ years ago, the practice of using custom fields is still most common with this cohort, while more recent adopters overwhelmingly default to using the relation table directly."
                        data={formData.parentInfo.sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.parentInfo)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.parentInfo}
                        legendLabel="Method"
                    />

                    <h3 id="sms-consent">5. SMS & Texting Consent</h3>
                    <p>
                        Engaging prospective students via text is a common
                        practice, but we observed that a significant proportion
                        of schools rely on passive disclaimer language rather
                        than standalone fields that capture explicit opt-in
                        consent.
                    </p><p>
                        Between regulations and carrier A2P compliance standards
                        requiring affirmative opt-ins, we recommend that schools
                        consult with their general counsel's office to ensure
                        their practices are compliant. Technolutions includes
                        suggested "Further reading about A2P 10DLC" in their <a
                            href="https://knowledge.technolutions.net/v1/docs/compliance-dashboard"
                            >Compliance Dashboard</a
                        > Knowledge Base article.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Notably, we also observed a trend of this disclaimer
                        language being expanded to include consent for
                        AI-generated calls or messages, adding another layer for
                        review.
                    </p>
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="SMS Consent Practices by Carnegie Classification"
                        caption="How institutions collect cell phone numbers and consent for text messaging."
                        data={formData.smsConsent.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.smsConsent)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.smsConsent}
                        legendLabel="Practice"
                    />
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="SMS Consent Practices by Size & Selectivity"
                        caption="Across school types, our recommendation is to have your OGC review your SMS consent practices regularly."
                        data={formData.smsConsent.sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.smsConsent)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.smsConsent}
                        legendLabel="Practice"
                    />

                    <h2 id="marketing-ux">Marketing & User Experience</h2>
                    <p>
                        Finally, we analyzed questions related to marketing
                        intelligence and user experience design patterns.
                    </p>

                    <h3>
                        <h3 id="marketing-attribution">
                            6. Marketing Attribution: "How Did You Hear About
                            Us?"
                        </h3>
                    </h3>
                    <p>
                        If stakeholders are pushing for greater clarity around
                        marketing attribution and the source of leads, adding a
                        question directly to the inquiry form can be tempting.
                        However, this is relatively uncommon across school
                        types, and adds to form length. If gathering this
                        information at point of inquiry is not affecting your
                        follow up outreach, it may be more beneficial to save
                        the collection of this data point for later in the
                        process.
                    </p>
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="Forms With Marketing Source Questions by Carnegie Classification"
                        caption="Percentage of forms that ask 'How did you hear about us?' or a similar question."
                        data={formData.marketingSource.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="Forms With Marketing Source Questions by Size & Selectivity"
                        caption="Overall, 11% of schools include a question like 'How did you hear about us?' on their inquiry forms."
                        data={formData.marketingSource
                            .sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Asks?"
                    />

                    <h3 id="optional-step">
                        7. Including Optional Steps: "Have Time for More?"
                    </h3>
                    <p>
                        One solution to the problem of overly long forms is to
                        give students the choice: you can either submit right
                        away, providing only the essential data points, or, if
                        you have a few moments, provide additional details.
                    </p><p>
                        As with collecting marketing attribution data, it's
                        important to make sure the data collected in these
                        optional sections is useful and helps inform the
                        relationship you're developing, rather than simply
                        collecting data for the sake of easier reporting. It's
                        worth asking whether these additional data points could
                        be collected instead as part of a follow-up, so that the
                        focus remains on the student's needs.
                    </p>
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="carnegie"
                        title="Forms With an Optional Final Step by Carnegie Classification"
                        caption="Percentage of forms that offer an optional section for more information."
                        data={formData.optionalStep.carnegieDistribution}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Has Step?"
                    />
                    <DistributionChart
                        type="small-multiples"
                        title="Forms With an Optional Final Step by Size & Selectivity"
                        caption="Larger, highly selective institutions were the outlier, with more than a third taking this approach."
                        data={formData.optionalStep.sizeSelectivityDistribution}
                        rowLabels={sizeLabels}
                        colLabels={selectivityLabels}
                        bucketOrder={Object.keys(buckets.binary)}
                        bucketConfig={buckets.binary}
                        legendLabel="Has Step?"
                    />

                    <h3 id="conclusion">
                        Conclusion: Revisiting Form Practices to Reduce Friction
                        for Prospective Students
                    </h3>
                    <p>
                        While every institution takes its own approach to
                        collecting inquiry data, it's important to understand
                        the evolving practices of your peer institutions and to regularly review how your own approach compares.</p> 
                    <p> A great inquiry form experience remains centered on the student: asking only what's needed to spark further discussion and build a relationship. Reducing the friction students experience in filling out your inquiry forms is our goal with this analysis, whether that involves cutting a few fields, changing how you're
                        collecting a key data point, or giving users an
                        experience that adapts to their preferences. </p><p>As you discuss your form questions with your team, we hope this analysis helps guide those conversations toward a student experience that is intentional and focused on building great relationships.
                    </p>
                    <em
                        >Looking for direction around your Slate data collection and reporting? Reach out to
                       <a href="mailto:info@predicatehighered.com"
                                >info@predicatehighered.com</a> to discuss how we can help.</em
                    >

                    <AuthorBlock />
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>
    <Insights />
    <Contact />
    <Footer />

    <style is:global>
        .content-section .article-content h2[id],
        .content-section .article-content h3[id] {
